In that state, a 2007 law incentivized school districts to merge as a way to save money amid declining student enrollment.
Often, so-called “good” school districts enjoy some of the highest property tax revenue-to-student ratios in the country.
In December 2018, Indiana’s State Board of Education released a memo reinterpreting existing laws to streamline the state’s onerous school secession process.
Taken together, these laws could result in the creation of four new, predominately white and affluent charter school districts operating outside the diverse Charlotte-Mecklenburg school district.
(Leaders of the Gardendale secession movement deny that their proposal was racially motivated.)